[normal]Examination of Witness[bold]Witness
[normal]:
[normal] 
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold], Chief Executive, Network Rail, gave evidence
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q1 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]Good afternoon, Sir David. Welcome to the Transport Select Committee. Could you give us your name and position for our records, please?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: David Higgins, Chief E
[normal]xecutive of Network Rail.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q2 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Sir David, it hasn’t escaped our notice 
[normal]that you are shortly to become c
[normal]hair of High Speed 2. Before we ask you questions about your current position
[normal],
[normal] I would like to raise some issues to do with High Speed 2. I am sure you are well aware of the mounting criticisms that have been voiced of High Speed 2 in recent weeks. In view of that background what do you see as your main challenges in taking up your new role?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: I should start by saying that I don’t t
[normal]ake up the role until January, t
[normal]herefore I have not been directly involved to date. When the business case is fully and transparently discussed in Parliament, as it should be, I think it will be very strong. It is a national project. It is a long-term project that deals with 
[normal]a
[normal] long-t
[normal]erm problem of public transport
[normal] that we have had in this nation for a long time. We use traditional methodologies of assessing it, and to date the methodology cuts out any growth three years after the project has finished. I suppose that is a commentary on the methodology. It might also be an indicator as to why it is very difficult to get major infrastructure in key parts of this country. When the full facts are laid out
[normal],
[normal] together with what I consider to be very conservative figures on growth of about 2% per annum assumed in the model going forward
[normal],
[normal] until it is capped three years after it has finished—which is less than half of what we are currently achieving—I think it will be a very strong case. I don’t think that will become the issue.
[normal]              
[normal]What will be the issue is giving the public and Parliament confidence that this major investment of public money can be done responsibly, in the most cost-effective way and that the communities to the north a
[normal]nd adjacent to the railway line
[normal] in the regions benefit the most. They should benefit fr
[normal]om schools, jobs, businesses 
[normal]and services 
[normal]that 
[normal]are freed up on the existing line. 
[normal]I am not sure we have done the right job, or the fullest job, of explaining that to those communities, listening to them and then delivering that.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q3 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] If the job of explaining that has not been done, who is to blame for that?  Should Ministers or High Speed 2 have been doing it?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: No one is to blame for it. It is a very complex project. 
[normal]A project of this size and scale
[normal] is going through a very complex parliamentary process. We need to explain to members of the public
[normal], first,
[normal] why a parliamentary process, 
[normal]which
[normal] will probably finish on the current schedule in 2020, takes so long, what is involved in that process and 
[normal]also 
[normal]the benefits.
[normal] 
[normal]To date everyone is focused on speed. Speed is an interesting part of 
[normal]i
[normal]t, but for me it has never been about speed. It has been about capacity. The bottom 
[normal]end
[normal] of the West Coast is full. We know that now; we can’t put any more train paths on it. Virgin applied to have one this year. Regrettably
[normal],
[normal] we turned down two paths from 
[normal]Shrewsbury
[normal] and 
[normal]Blackpool
[normal]. We know the bottom end is full, but the main benefit I see is connectivity. 
[normal]It is connectivity from the north. 
[normal]There is a north-south connectivity
[normal],
[normal] but there is also a connectivity betwee
[normal]n the great cities of the north, which w
[normal]e need to explain and show the benefits of. We also need to get the maximum benefit from what this will do to regeneration in major cities in the north. We need to explain how that will happen now and that these cities won’t in some way be blighted for years to come. It should be quite the contrary; it should be a fantastic opportunity 
[normal]that
[normal] we need to explain to business.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q4 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Karen Lumley:[bold] What made you want to take on the role? How do you think you are going to do a different job of changing people’s hearts and minds?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: I became concerned that a project 
[normal]that
[normal] has always had bipartisan political support was becoming a bit of a political football. It is too important for that. It is a national project 
[normal]that
[normal] is crucially important for the nation
[normal] to spread wealth but
[normal] also crucially important for the railway infrastructure. We cannot keep going on patching up the existing one for the next 50 years.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q5 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Karen Lumley:[bold] 
[normal]How are you going to do it differently 
[normal]from
[normal] what HS2 have been doing so far?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: I will just build on what they have done. If you look at what they have had to do in the last few years to get to the stage where the Bill will be lodged in Parliament within the next six weeks, 
[normal]it
[normal] is an amazing achievement. It is way ahead of where Crossrail got to. I know Doug Oakervee very well and have enormous respect for him. I want 
[normal]a
[normal] smooth baton change between Doug and myself so that I can pick up the work that he has done so well to date.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q6 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Sanders:[bold] You mentioned connectivity
[normal],
[normal] but h
[normal]ow does connectivity in this project help the far south-
[normal]west of 
[normal]England
[normal], which a
[normal]t the moment 
[normal]has
[normal] some of the slowest journey times and the hig
[normal]hest fares?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: High Speed 2 is not a case of either/or. It is not a case of either/or even on the traditional line
[normal]—
[normal]the West Coast. We will spend more money in the 20 years that High Speed 2 will be built on upgrading the existing network
[normal] than we will on High Speed 2. O
[normal]n the Western there is a £7 billion project, 
[normal]on 
[normal]which I am sure you are well briefed, which takes electrification to 
[normal]Cardiff
[normal] and then on to 
[normal]Swansea
[normal] and the valleys. It will bring it at the moment down to 
[normal]Bristol
[normal],
[normal] but that will improve line speed on the whole section on the Western not only by electrification—
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q7 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Sanders:[bold] Could I ask you to sto
[normal]p there and maybe look at a map and I will ask the question again?
[normal] How does it hel
[normal]p connectivity in the far south-
[normal]west of 
[normal]England
[normal]?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: Within the far south-
[normal]west
[normal],
[normal] it is subject to further investment no doubt both in this control period but also in the next control period. It means 
[normal]that its core route, so
[normal] moving from the 
[normal]Thames
[normal] 
[normal]Valley
[normal] and areas t
[normal]hrough to 
[normal]Bristol
[normal] further south,
[normal] 
[normal]t
[normal]hat line now—
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q8 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Sanders:[bold] 
[normal]Sorry—
[normal]I
[normal] am talking about the far south-
[normal]west. 
[normal]Bristol
[normal] is the south
[normal] midlands and not the far south-
[normal]west.
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: 
[normal]Okay. The
[normal] major investment programme 
[normal]at the moment, 
[normal]with a lot of work at 
[normal]Bristol
[normal] and Bristol Temple Meads, means that—
[normal]Mr Sanders:[bold] That is not the far south-
[normal]west.
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: —is where we stop, if we carve off south-
[normal]west 
[normal]England
[normal] at that point. 
[normal]Then w
[normal]e will look at continuing improvements. In fact we have already put a proposal through to the Department 
[normal]of how we put
[normal] more investment down to Exeter and the whole areas 
[normal]that were 
[normal]substantially impacted, connectivity-wise, during the 
[normal]wettest summer we had last year—what can be done to make sure that that area is not so exposed and not cut off as it was last time—and w
[normal]e have put a case through to the Department to consider 
[normal]that
[normal].
[normal]              [bold]Mr Sanders:[bold] That is just protecting existing connectivity. It is not improving the connectivity in the area.
[normal]              [bold]Chair:[bold] I am sure we will be returning to this at another date, Mr Sanders.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q9 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Martin Vickers:[bold] Sir David, you mentioned connectivity between the
[normal] major cities of the north and h
[normal]ow it will help regeneration. Could you expand a little on how you think it will help the more provincial towns in the north, in terms of freeing up capacity so that they too may have more direct services to 
[normal]London
[normal] and other major cities?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: That is a huge opportunity. Everyone talks about Leeds to 
[normal]London
[normal] or 
[normal]Birmingham
[normal] to 
[normal]London
[normal]. The other day I went to 
[normal]Milton Keynes
[normal]. I had business in 
[normal]York
[normal]. It was quicker to come down to Euston, walk across to King’s Cross, have a cup of coffee and then go back up to 
[normal]York
[normal]. That 
[normal]is actually
[normal] three and a half hours if you go the other way
[normal]. That will be cut dramatically—more than halved
[normal].
[normal]              
[normal]There are at least a dozen major cities in the midlands where their journeys between cities will be much better. The huge benefit, which I don’t think we have properly set out to the public, is what it doe
[normal]s in relieving the main line—
[normal]the West Coast. By having 18 
[normal]new train paths on the new high-
[normal]speed line
[normal],
[normal] it means that we can fre
[normal]e up the West Coast for freight of course, but t
[normal]hat provides huge capacity
[normal] to look at services
[normal]. 
[normal]              
[normal]At the moment I travel on London Midland services quite a lot. I stand quite a lot as I go into 
[normal]Coventry
[normal] or 
[normal]Birmingham
[normal],
[normal] and not even in peak hours. There will be more stopping services between the cities of 
[normal]Coventry
[normal], Rugby, 
[normal]Milton Keynes
[normal] and all these areas. There will be an improved service from Stafford and 
[normal]Liverpool
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q10 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Martin Vickers:[bold] Would you expand a bit on the East Coast too? I represent the Cleethorpes constituency in northern 
[normal]Lincolnshire
[normal]. As the Prime Minister pointed out in his speech to the conference, northern 
[normal]Lincolnshire
[normal] and the 
[normal]Humber
[normal] area is a major centre for the renewables sector. 
[normal]Potential investors are looking for connectivity not just to 
[normal]London
[normal] but to other major cities. Would you anticipate that towns such as 
[normal]Grimsby
[normal], Cleethorpes and 
[normal]Scunthorpe
[normal] could also gain additional services?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: Yes. The key thing about this design 
[normal]that
[normal] I find most attractive is that it is not a replacement for the West Coast. It is a central spine. It connects to the East Coast and it connects into Sheffield to the 
[normal]East Midlands
[normal] services. The real challenge and the crucial part on the East
[normal] Coast is the two-track railway, which
[normal] is incredibly restrictive because we are mixing freight, commuter and high speed. It will release a lot more services
[normal],
[normal] and those who come on at 
[normal]York
[normal] or 
[normal]Leeds
[normal] of course can divert on t
[normal]o the high-speed 
[normal]line.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q11 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Graham Stringer:[bold] When Philip Hammond was Secretary of State
[normal] he had a rule of thumb that the rate of investment in High Speed 2 should be 
[normal]roughly 
[normal]the rate of investment that 
[normal]there 
[normal]had been in Crossrail, which was about £2 billion a year. Do you think that is a reasonable rule of thumb
[normal],
[normal] or could High Speed 2 be built more quickly
[normal],
[normal] because it is going to give us significant economic benefits?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: If you are in the north you will want to see the benefits earlier. I don’t think people will want to wait until 2032 or 2035 to see the benefits. That is something I will look at closely.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q12 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Graham Stringer:[bold] One of the things this Committee recommended in its report on High Speed 2 was that
[normal],
[normal] as well as building from south to north
[normal],
[normal] it should look at building from north to south. Would you consider that? Do you think that is a sensible recommendation?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: We should certainly look at it. 
[normal]At the moment it is driven by the legislative process. The current timetable has the Royal Assent for the second stage in 2020. That is a long way from now. You could build stage one of High Speed 2 between now a
[normal]nd Royal Assent for the second B
[normal]ill. Surely we can make that quicker, if we can. All options are open.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q13 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Graham Stringer:[bold] You mentioned the methodology for the assessment of High Speed 2. Could you expand on that a little? Do you think the methodology for assessing costs and benefits 
[normal]is faulty at all—
[normal]or 
[normal]could 
[normal]it 
[normal]be improved?
[normal] That is probably a better way of putting it.
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: Let us 
[normal]just 
[normal]look at history. The Jubilee Line extension did not pass 
[normal]a
[normal] value-for-money test. Thankfully it was built. High Speed 1 nearly fell over but for the Secretary of State intervening in the project. Crossrail 1 and Thameslink are both 20 years late because they failed value-for-money tests at the tim
[normal]e; and clearly they don’t 
[normal]now. 
[normal]              
[normal]While I have not gone through the value for money in detail, 
[normal]it is probably right to put in 
[normal]the growth as
[normal]sumption of 2%, 
[normal]though it is very conservative
[normal], of w
[normal]here we are cu
[normal]rrently in terms of rail demand. E
[normal]verything we have built has outstripped all 
[normal]of 
[normal]our projections.
[normal] If you look at a 20-year timetable and you start the 
[normal]assessment or 
[normal]modelling in 2015, 
[normal]you 
[normal]shut it off 
[normal]in terms of growth 
[normal]in 2035. I und
[normal]erstand that for most projects—
[normal]but not for a project that does not finish until 2033. In terms of the growth you only get two years of benefit and then it flattens off
[normal],
[normal] because that is what the model says. That has got to be wrong, hasn’t it?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q14 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Graham Stringer:[bold] I agree with that. There has been a lot of debate about whether business people can work on High Speed 2. I am not sure whether they do or they don’t. I have always thought that is irrelevant. The real benefit of the project is capacity and induced economic growth in different parts of the country. Do you think the part of the economic assessment that deals with the time saving—the fact that 
[normal]a
[normal] business person can be in their office that bit longer—should be scrapped from the assessment system?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: You are right, provided that business people can sit down, of course. Currently around 100,000 people a day coming into 
[normal]London
[normal] stand
[normal],
[normal] and that is not going to get any better unless we work on capacity. 
[normal]You will find that element of the case for justifying it will be reduced in the new strategic business plan.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q15 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Graham Stringer:[bold] Do you accept the figures in the recent KPMG report 
[normal]which indicate
[normal] that High Speed 2 would be paid for in 30 years by increased revenue into the Treasury?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: I have not been through that detail, to be honest.
[normal]Graham Stringer:[bold] If you haven’t, you haven’t.
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: All I would say is that the upgrade on West Coast had a certain level of forecast. There is a 70% increase in patronage in 10 years from 
[normal]Manchester
[normal] to 
[normal]London
[normal] and
[normal] a 60% increase from 
[normal]Birmingham
[normal] to 
[normal]London
[normal]. There was a business plan based on that. They have already hit 30% of that target within a very short period of time. We have outstripped the business case for the West Coast route modernisation, as it was called, because traffic growth has been far in excess of what anyone predicted.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q16 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Iain Stewart:[bold] In both the context of HS2 and the rail system more generally there has been some recent comment that capacity issues could be helped, if not solved, by getting rid of first class and converting those carriages to standard class accommodation. Do you think that is a red herring or is there some merit in that?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: I read something about that today. That is really for the train operating companies to work through with the Department. There are lots of things you can do. All of them are small and incremental and they will eke a little bit more out of the existing system. What High Speed 2 does is make a monumental increase in capacity. There will be 18 new train paths. Train paths are like landing slots at Heathrow. They are very valuable and you can’t invent new ones. At the 
[normal]moment Virgin on West Coast has
[normal] about 10 or 12 an hour, but 18 new ones could potentially take 1,000 people each. That is a massive increase in capacity. When it opens
[normal],
[normal] it will also take around half a million lorry movements off the existing road network by creating capacity on the West Coast. If you were to build the motorway equivalent of that
[normal],
[normal] it is about two new motorways. There is the passenger capacity as well as the freight 
[normal]that
[normal] is freed up on the existing line. It is that huge leap in capacity 
[normal]that
[normal] is the crucial prize in this whole major project.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q17 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Iain Stewart:[bold] I have one last question on HS2. Last year the Secretary of State announced that he was going to look at the feasibility of extending HS2 towards 
[normal]Scotland
[normal]. Are you able to give us any update on what work is being done on that?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: No, I can’t. All I would say is that in control periods 5, 6 and 7, which will be over the timetable, there has to be development on the existing network
[normal],
[normal] including the section north of Preston—that is 
[normal]Scotland
[normal]—to get maximum benefit out of High Speed 2. I am sure that will happen.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q18 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Part of the case for High Speed 2 is developing new services for passengers and freight on the freed-up lines. Whose responsibility is it to make sure that work is actually done?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: It is Network Rail’s responsibility to advise High Speed 2 and the Department. We have done that and put work into that. We did a public study about six months ago about the availability. I wouldn’t try working out winners and losers
[normal],
[normal] because by building this extra capacity there is time over the next years to work out how best to use that.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q19 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] What would happen if high-speed rail
[normal] was folded into Network Rail and stopped being a separate organisation?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: No matter what happens
[normal],
[normal] I believe that both High Speed 2 and Network Rail need to work incredibly closely together. The 
[normal]key thing is the network itself—
[normal]how you make sure that the train services on the existing network, freight 
[normal]and so on
[normal], tie into 
[normal]what will be 
[normal]quite a few junction point
[normal]s where you can get on the high-
[normal]speed network. It is what we call a system operator. You need a controlling mind that works out how you prioritise traffic not only in the good times but when you have disruption on the network. It is essential that the tw
[normal]o organisations work together. On w
[normal]hether they can be one organisation in a project of this size and scale—and you might call me conflicted here—it would not be surprising if the Secretary of State would want a fairly heavy hand to know what is going on from a project point of view
[normal],
[normal] because it is such a mammoth project. I think you will find that
[normal],
[normal] with High Speed 2
[normal],
[normal] the Department and Network Rail will reach agreement in the coming months on how that relationship works.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q20 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] There is a lot of concern that investment in High Speed 2 could starve necessary investment in the existing classic line. Do you see any evidence of that happening?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: I don’t see that. I see strong support from both the Government and the regulator to continue to invest. We have virtually finished the control period 5 negotiations to take us through to 2019. That is again a record investment in the existing network. Work has alrea
[normal]dy started on control period 6
[normal], which
[normal] takes us to 2024
[normal], 
[normal]and 
[normal]the 
[normal]schemes involve
[normal]d 
[normal]a
[normal]cross
[normal] 
[normal]the
[normal] nation 
[normal]mean
[normal] 
[normal]that
[normal] it
[normal] won’t be starved of funds. I do believe 
[normal]longer-
[normal]term 
[normal]that you need to look at how the two projects are funded and the long-term sustainability of all that, but I don’t see any evidence that the existing network will be starved of funds.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q21 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Improving efficiency in the railways will be an ongoing issue for both 
[normal]high-
[normal]speed rail and the classic line. You have been chairing the Rail Delivery Group
[normal],
[normal] which was set up to improve working between different parts of the rail industry and improve efficiency. What have you actually been able to deliver?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: First, I was deput
[normal]y chair. Tim O’Toole from First
[normal]Group has been a very competent chair, I have to say. The first thing we have been able to do is enable the CEOs of the rail operating companies, freight and Network Rail, with the support of ATOC, to meet every month. We discuss the industry’s major issues. 
[normal]One of the big commentaries of the McNulty report on the rail industry was that there was no leadership and a very fragmented railway. We do have one of the most fragmented railways in the world with the way our system is set up. The Rail Delivery Group was the industry’s response to McNulty, saying that we can take a leadership position. It is everything from the franchising rounds right through to issues on smart ticketing and technology, which we are heavily involved in, and through to access. 
[normal]O
[normal]ne of the major challenge
[normal]s we face with a huge workload—a record workload—on the network 
[normal]is how we get more efficient access and 
[normal]are
[normal] quicker on and off the track when we need to maintain or do major work. There is a lot of 
[normal]good 
[normal]work going on there. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q22 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] What have you actually been able to achieve?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: Pilot projects. We have projects where we have changed timetables, whether it 
[normal]is
[normal] in 
[normal]Kent
[normal] or the east midlands. We have been able to make 
[normal]available 
[normal]more weekend time slots for 
[normal]weekend 
[normal]travel for the public. We are getting more efficient access mid
[normal]-
[normal]week to be able to maintain and do capital upgrades on the projects.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q23 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] One of the areas you have been looking at is the franchises. What has improved there?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: There has been a great combination. Everyone expected, with the natural comm
[normal]ercial tensions within the rail-
[normal]owning groups, that they would be competing with each other. In response to Richard Brown’s study
[normal],
[normal] the RDG came out as a single voice with a series of 11 recommendations. They were done in a private consultation with the Department and with Richard Brown. I am pleased to say that all of those recommendations were very seriously considered and most of them taken up. That is the first time that the industry has spoken with a single voice. I think even the Department was somewha
[normal]t surprised at how unified they
[normal] were. In the end
[normal],
[normal] the result that came out of the report and from Peter Wilkinson’s work within the Department has been very constructive.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q24 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Are £3.5 billion of efficiency savings going to be achieved by 2019?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: If we go back to 2005
[normal],
[normal] we were an industry 
[normal]of 
[normal]over £7 billion. By 2019
[normal],
[normal] we forecast the industry’s public subsidy 
[normal]to
[normal] the railway to be around £2.6 billion. Will we achieve £3.5 billion? 
[normal]W
[normal]e will achieve a target
[normal], we think,
