[normal]Q35 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Why have the delays on rail attributable to Network Rail increased so much? You have not met your targets, have you?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: In terms of the overall targets, there are a lot of them. If I am allowed the indulgence of this Committee to go back a fraction, the fi
[normal]rst thing is that we have learned
[normal] a lot—both ourselves as Network Rail and the regulator—since the targets were set in 2008 in a time of recession. There are three things that affect our targets that were not considered at the time when the targets were set.
[normal]              
[normal]The first thing is that extreme weather was not considered and isn’t provided for in our settl
[normal]ement. If I look at the last 10 years from 2000, in the last 100
[normal] years
[normal], of
[normal] the f
[normal]ive most extreme weather events and
[normal] the wettest years on record
[normal],
[normal] four have happened since 2000. The fifth of course was in 1954. Extreme weather was never allowed in it. Of course, last year it was the wettest summer on record, flowing through into winter. The Victorian railways are not set up for that. When we have extreme weather we do one thing. We operate our railways safely but we don’t cancel trains. We had a huge number of delay minutes last summer because we made a conscious decision to keep running trains. We thought that it was more important to move people than it was to cancel trains.
[normal]              
[normal]The second issue is that
[normal],
[normal] when the settlement was made and the targets were set
[normal],
[normal] the major project
[normal]s
[normal] work on the railways was much less than it is today. I can give a simple example. Crossrail was not in the settlement. It was not in the control period 4 settlement; neither was electrification. We are doing all those b
[normal]illions of pounds-
[normal]worth of work
[normal] above and beyond. I would love every project to be finished, but
[normal],
[normal] as those who travelled on the railway this morning will know
[normal],
[normal] there are a few overruns. We are doing a massiv
[normal]e amount of work on the railway
[normal] now and that affects us.
[normal]              
[normal]The third issue is growth. When the growth was set in 2008 it allowed for overall growth of around 6% of the railway network. It has turned out to be around 9%. The oft
[normal]-
[normal] quoted figure of PPM—public performance measure, as it 
[normal]is 
[normal]called—is about trains, not about people or passengers. What I can say is that by the end of this control period, every year 200 million more people will arrive on time than they did at the start of the control period.  Why is that? It is because every month we are providing 13,000 additional train services than were allowed for in the bid. That means we are moving a lot more people on time and ahead of what was in the control period bid, but if you just measure 
[normal]PPM, if you just measure 
[normal]when a train arrives on time
[normal],
[normal] then
[normal],
[normal] because we are running a lot more trains than we expected to
[normal],
[normal] the public performance measure is flat. It is flat at around 91% of trains within the acceptable performance figures. That is the reason why that has occurred.
