[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: The first thing we are really focused on is autumn. The biggest area of impact is 
[normal]Kent
[normal]. That is by far the most exposed route. We have done a responsible vegetation-clearing programme with heavy consultation
[normal],
[normal] after a shaky start a year or so ago. The team there have done a fantastic job. Of course, autumn i
[normal]s all about train crews as well and making
[normal] sure that 
[normal]the
[normal] rails are properly 
[normal]repaired
[normal]. You lose autumn in the first week if a driver is concerned that the rails aren’t properly 
[normal]repaired 
[normal]and they are concerned about overrunning a signal. Trains all slow down and we lose performance dramatically.
[normal]              
[normal]In terms of winter, we have put in a massive amount of effort. We are particularly working with our train operating company partners. The biggest issue for both autumn and winter is drivers. We need the right number of drivers to be able to operate the trains. These are one-off events and we need to draw on a limited resource of drivers to be able to crew these road vehicles and trains that we set up especially for this. We are ready and very focused. I was up in 
[normal]Scotland
[normal] the other week making sure that the team up there are particularly focused. We expect them to be the first impacted.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q71 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Are six snow and ice treatment trains enough?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: They are if they are properly used, they get proper access to the network and we have the right number of trains. We think we are in a substantially better position than we were. It is not only that; it is rail heating. We have done extensive work on the third rail here in the south of 
[normal]London
[normal] in the last two years.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q72 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] One of the issues raised last year was the lack of good information for people at the time they needed it. What are you doing to improve that?
[normal]Sir David Higgins[bold]: We are working closely with our train operating company customers. We use modern media a lot more. Our Twitter sites and the work we do with that have been very effective. Each rail company does it differently but we work very closely with them to get that information out. We can never be satisfied with the level of passenger information compared 
[normal]with
[normal] some other industries, but the industry is putting out a huge amount of information and effort. You will see that transparency is something that the Rail Delivery Group takes very seriously.
[normal]&#xa0;
